SIMPLE: plug
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Plug
<hw>Plug</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Akin to D.
<ets>plug</ets>, G. <ets>pflock</ets>, Dan. <ets>pl⟦oum⟧k</ets>,
<ets>plug</ets>, Sw. <ets>plugg</ets>; cf. W. <ets>ploc</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Any piece of wood, metal, or other substance used to
stop or fill a hole; a stopple.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A flat oblong cake of pressed tobacco.</def>
<mark>[U. S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A high, tapering silk hat.</def> <mark>[Slang,
U.S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A worthless horse.</def> <mark>[Slang,
U.S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Building)</fld> <def>A block of wood let into a
wall, to afford a hold for nails.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>An act of plugging{6}; a brief mention for the sake
of publicity or advertisement, especially during a public event not
specifically intended for advertising purposes; <as>as, he put in a
<ex>plug</ex> for his favorite charity</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Breech plug</b></col> <fld>(Gun.)</fld>, <cd>in
breech-loading guns, the metal plug or cylinder which closes the
aperture in the breech, through which the gun is loaded.</cd> --
<col><b>Fire plug</b></col>, <cd>a street hydrant to which hose may be
attached.</cd> <mark>[U. S.]</mark> -- <col><b>Hawse plug</b></col>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a plug to stop a hawse hole.</cd> --
<col><b>Plug and feather</b></col>. <fld>(Stone Working)</fld> <cd>See
<er>Feather</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 7.</cd> -- <col><b>Plug
centerbit</b></col>, <cd>a centerbit ending in a small cylinder instead
of a point, so as to follow and enlarge a hole previously made, or to
form a counterbore around it.</cd> -- <col><b>Plug rod</b></col>
<fld>(Steam Eng.)</fld> <cd>, a rod attached to the beam for working the
valves, as in the Cornish engine.</cd> -- <col><b>Plug valve</b></col>
<fld>(Mech.)</fld>, <cd>a tapering valve, which turns in a case like the
<xex>plug</xex> of a faucet.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plug</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Plug
<hw>Plug</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Plugged</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Plugging</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <def>To stop with a
plug; to make tight by stopping a hole.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To briefly publicize or advertise, especially during
a public event not specifically intended for advertising purposes;
<as>as, during the interview he <ex>plugged</ex> his new
book</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> put in a plug for.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plug board</ent>⟦br⟧
